{
  "text": "SLC29A1 was expressed in 83% of the AML patients [CITATION_1] . The results of the studies on the association between SLC29A1 of human AML blasts and clinical drug response were not consistent. Previous data showed that there was no association between SLC29A1 and Ara-C sensitivity [CITATION_2] . However, some studies demonstrated close correlation of SLC29A1 with Ara-C resistance, treatment response and survival of patients with AML. The inhibition of SLC29A1 expression may induce Ara-C resistance; thereby reduce the overall survival of patients with AML [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . FLT3-ITD indicates poor prognosis in AML, and one of the mechanisms involved was to suppress the expression of SLC29A1 to induce Ara-C resistance in AML patients [CITATION_5] .",
